\subtree{
\title{RL Alignment Results (dt=0.1)}
\pre{\startverb
| Policy | GradAlign | MeanConc | GF3 Balance | Mean Reward |
|--------|-----------|----------|-------------|-------------|
| Oracle | +0.415 | 0.226 | no | +0.503 |
| PPO | +0.239 | 0.526 | no | -0.041 |
| Langevin | -0.084 | 0.448 | **YES** | +0.089 |
| Random | -0.469 | 0.032 | no | -0.958 |
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Key finding}: PPO has higher gradient alignment but \strong{breaks GF(3) conservation}. Langevin is the ONLY policy that conserves the tripartite structure. This is Goodhart's Law: optimizing the reward metric doesn't preserve structural invariants.}
}

